          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"week_number\":1,\"phase_type\":\"Base\",\"weekly_target_km\":55,\"is_deload_week\":false,\"days\":[{\"day_of_week\":0,\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"notes\":\"20 km easy long run at 5:22–5:56/km. Keep it conversational — this is your aerobic anchor for the week. Cap at 120 min.\"},{\"day_of_week\":1,\"slot_type\":\"Rest\",\"workout_type\":null,\"notes\":\"Full rest day. Recovery is where adaptation happens — this is an active investment in Sunday's effort.\"},{\"day_of_week\":2,\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"notes\":\"8 km easy at 5:22–5:56/km. Shake out the legs from Sunday. If you feel flat, lean toward the slower end.\"},{\"day_of_week\":3,\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"Tempo\",\"notes\":\"12 km total: 2 km warm-up, 8 km at threshold pace (4:28/km), 2 km cool-down. This is your primary quality session — threshold work maintains your lactate ceiling without building fatigue.\"},{\"day_of_week\":4,\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"notes\":\"6 km easy recovery run at 5:45–5:56/km. Lean toward the slower end — this is active recovery, not a fitness session.\"},{\"day_of_week\":5,\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"Interval\",\"notes\":\"10 km total: 2 km warm-up, 5×1 km at interval pace (4:11/km) with 400 m jog recovery, ~1.6 km cool-down. VO2max stimulus to keep your aerobic ceiling sharp.\"},{\"day_of_week\":6,\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"notes\":\"8 km easy at 5:22–5:56/km. A comfortable, relaxed effort to round out the week. No watch-chasing today.\"}],\"week_summary\":\"Welcome, Maria — and what a foundation you're bringing into this maintenance phase. Your recent training shows real consistency: a 63 km week with quality sessions executed right on pace, and a 21 km long run in the bank. That's the kind of work that earns a plan like this.\\n\\nWeek 1 holds you at 55 km — your stated current volume — with a structure that mirrors what's already working for you: one long run, one tempo, one interval session, and easy running filling the rest. The goal here isn't to build; it's to sustain the aerobic fitness and race-ready sharpness you've developed over 12 years of smart training.\\n\\nA note on the Achilles: given your 2023 history on the left side, the easy days are genuinely important — not filler. Running the recovery runs at the slower end of easy pace (5:45–5:56/km) keeps tendon load manageable across a 6-day week. If you ever notice any tightness there, that's worth flagging before it becomes a pattern.\\n\\nYour VDOT of 46.7 reflects your best fitness — the 1:38 half on a flat course in ideal conditions. The paces in this plan are derived directly from that benchmark. Trust them, especially on easy days when they might feel slower than you'd like. That's the plan working, not a sign you're going backwards.\\n\\nWhat does your week look like in terms of when you prefer to do the harder sessions? That'll help us make sure Thursday's tempo and Saturday's intervals land on days when you're freshest.\"}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
